				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
					<h2 class="elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default">BÀI CHỮA MẪU</h2>				</div>
				</div>
		<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-60c97ae sample-response e-flex e-con-boxed e-con e-child" data-id="60c97ae" data-element_type="container"><div><h2>Revised Essay</h2><p><b>(Based On Your Ideas)</b></p><p>The question of animal rights is increasingly prominent in modern society, sparking considerable debate.  A growing number of people advocate for the cessation of animal exploitation and the granting of rights equal to those of humans. Conversely, others maintain that the utilization of animals is necessary to fulfill various human needs, encompassing food production and scientific research.</p><p>Public disapproval of animal exploitation is rising.  For instance, the declining popularity of circuses featuring animal acts demonstrates a shift in public preference towards human-centric entertainment.  Furthermore, legislation now protects animals from abuse, imposing fines and, in some cases, imprisonment for offenders.  Concerns also extend to animal breeding practices, with growing awareness of the often cruel methods employed in the slaughter of animals for food.</p><p>A new generation is developing a heightened sensitivity to animal welfare. However, this increased awareness is accompanied by the emergence of extremist viewpoints. While vegetarianism is gaining popularity, some hold distorted beliefs about animal rights.  A particular area of concern is animal research, which contributes significantly to advancements in medical science and improves human welfare.  Unfortunately, misinformation spread by extremist animal rights groups undermines this vital research.</p><p>For example, a recent incident saw an animal rights group sabotage years of neurological research by releasing laboratory rats, claiming the animals were cruelly treated.  This action was taken despite the use of anesthesia during each procedure.  While I strongly advocate for animal rights and oppose animal exploitation, I equally reject extremist actions that hinder crucial medical advancements.</p><h2>Sample Essay</h2><p><b>(Band 8.5 - 9.0)</b></p><p>The ethical treatment of animals is a subject of ongoing contention.  While a significant portion of the population champions animal rights, advocating for the cessation of exploitation and the granting of rights equivalent to those of humans, a counterargument persists that humans require animals to meet various needs, including food and research.</p><p>The increasing awareness of animal welfare is evident in several societal shifts.  The declining popularity of circuses featuring animal acts exemplifies a growing public aversion to animal exploitation for entertainment.  Moreover, stringent legal frameworks are increasingly implemented to protect animals from cruelty, with penalties ranging from substantial fines to imprisonment for offenders.  The ethical concerns extend to agricultural practices, with a rising demand for transparency and humane treatment throughout the food production chain.</p><p>However, the movement towards greater animal welfare is not without its challenges.  While vegetarianism and veganism are gaining traction, representing a shift in consumer preferences, extremist views within the animal rights movement pose a significant counterpoint.  These groups often impede crucial scientific research, particularly in the biomedical field, where animal models are essential for developing life-saving treatments and furthering medical understanding.</p><p>The potential benefits of animal research in advancing human health and well-being must be carefully weighed against ethical considerations.  While the humane treatment of animals used in research is paramount, the complete cessation of such research could severely hamper medical progress.  A balanced approach is therefore required, one that prioritizes ethical conduct while recognizing the vital role animals can play in scientific advancement.</p></div></div>
